      "symbol": "NDArrayBackedExtensionArray",
      "description": "An ExtensionArray subclass that wraps a single NumPy ndarray as its backing storage (_ndarray attribute). This class enables pandas to work with NumPy arrays as extension arrays, providing a bridge between raw NumPy arrays and pandas data structures. It implements the ExtensionArray interface while maintaining direct access to the underlying NumPy array, enabling transparent interoperability."
    },
    {
      "repo": "scipy/scipy",
      "path": "scipy/stats/_stats_py.py",
      "symbol": "describe",
      "description": "A statistical function that accepts array-like inputs (including NumPy arrays and pandas Series) and computes multiple descriptive statistics including count, min/max, mean, variance, skewness, and kurtosis. The function validates inputs through array_namespace protocols and delegates to array operations including xp.min(), xp.max(), xp.mean(), _var(), skew(), and kurtosis() for comprehensive statistical characterization."
    }
  ],
  "text": "Data flows through the scientific Python ecosystem via a layered architecture where each library adds functionality to the preceding layer.\n\n**Array Computation Layer (numpy/numpy)**: At the foundation, numpy/numpy provides the canonical array aggregation function sum() in numpy/_core/fromnumeric.py. This function accepts array-like inputs and performs element-wise summation via the _wrapreduction() mechanism, which dispatches to the add universal function's reduce() method. The function supports axis selection, dtype specification, keepdims retention, and initial value control. This is the low-level primitive for all numerical aggregations.\n\n**Data Structure Layer (pandas-dev/pandas)**: pandas-dev/pandas extends NumPy by wrapping raw arrays through the NDArrayBackedExtensionArray class in pandas/core/arrays/_mixins.py. This class inherits from both NDArrayBacked (a Cython base class) and ExtensionArray (the pandas extension array interface), storing the actual NumPy ndarray in the _ndarray attribute. This architecture allows pandas to maintain transparency with NumPy—operations on pandas extension arrays backed by NDArrayBackedExtensionArray delegate to the underlying NumPy array, enabling seamless integration. Subclasses like Categorical, DatetimeArray, and TimedeltaArray all build on this foundation.\n\n**Scientific Computation Layer (scipy/scipy)**: scipy/scipy consumes arrays from both numpy and pandas through the describe() function in scipy/stats/_stats_py.py. The describe() function accepts array_like inputs (supporting both raw NumPy arrays and pandas Series), validates them using array_namespace protocols, and then applies multiple statistical operations: min/max via xp.min() and xp.max(), central tendency via xp.mean(), dispersion via _var(), and shape measures via skew() and kurtosis(). The function returns a DescribeResult namedtuple containing comprehensive summary statistics.\n\n**Integration Pattern**: A user starting with raw data flows through this stack as follows: (1) create a NumPy array using standard creation functions, (2) optionally wrap it in a pandas Series/DataFrame using NDArrayBackedExtensionArray for labeled access and convenience methods, (3) pass the array or Series to scipy.stats.describe() which internally extracts the NumPy array and applies statistical transformations. This layered design maintains clear separation of concerns—numpy handles computation, pandas provides data structures, and scipy applies domain-specific statistical analysis—while preserving performance through direct array access at each level."
}

